I am wondering wethere there is compile warning/errro we can use when initing a ULL to OBD_OBJECT_EOF. This would helps to find all the places with this problem.

Another choice is to replace all usage of loff_t to __u64 unless interacting with VFS. This would reduce the possibility of problems caused by OBD_OBJECT_EOF and LLONG_MAX.

Patch Set 4:

Yeah, agreed difference between OBD_OBJECT_EOF/__u64 and LLONG_MAX/loff_t could cause a lot of tricky problems, e.g. the comparison of singed/unsigned values, and the two different ways of determination of EOF. And these problems could hide there forever until an unlucky user hit it in a corner case.

I am wondering whether the following cleanup can fix the potential problems once for all:

1) Replace loff_t to __u64 in all Lustre internal codes. For example, do not allow any structure defined in Lustre use loff_t, unless it is an API. It might be possible to add a rule in the code check script to prevent this usage?

2) Only use loff_t in defintions of APIs (functions, structures) and the interaction with Linux/ZFS/Ldiskfs.

3) If need to convert between loff_t and __u64, always use inline functions like:

static inline __u64 loff2ull(loff_t offset) {
	/* Assuming Linux/APIs never use negative offset value */
	LASSERT(offset >= 0);
	if (offset == LLONG_MAX)
		return OBD_OBJECT_EOF;
	return (__u64)offset;
}

static inline loff_t ull2loff(__u64 value) {
	loff_t offset;

	/* Assuming Linux/APIs never use negative offset value */
	if (value == OBD_OBJECT_EOF)
		return LLONG_MAX;

	offset = (loff_t)value;
	/* Assuming never use unsgined 64-bit offset larger than LLONG_MAX */
	LASSERT(value >= 0);
	return offset;
}

That would be many lines of codes, but would simplify the logic of using loff_t.
